{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17218"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71166"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9908"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71166"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a sudden onset of a severe, diffuse bifrontal headache and shortness of breath. She has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. Her regular medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure is 190/120 mmHg, respiratory rate is 24/min, SpO2 is 95% on room air, and temperature is 37.2\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals no focal deficits, but there are signs of end-organ damage, including retinal haemorrhages on fundoscopy and elevated creatinine levels on laboratory testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal arteritis","Neoplasm","Hypertensive crisis","Meningitis","Low cerebrospinal fluid pressure headache"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of severe headache, elevated blood pressure, and signs of end-organ damage such as retinal haemorrhages and renal impairment is consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertensive crisis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition requires immediate medical attention to prevent further complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with headache, jaw claudication, and visual disturbances, but it is not associated with acute severe hypertension or end-organ damage as described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E could cause headache and neurological symptoms, but it would not typically present with acute severe hypertension and end-organ damage in this manner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E often presents with headache, fever, neck stiffness, and altered mental status, but it is not associated with acute severe hypertension and end-organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow cerebrospinal fluid pressure headache\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a positional headache that worsens when upright and improves when lying down, and it is not associated with severe hypertension or end-organ damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertensive crisis is characterised by severely elevated blood pressure with evidence of acute end-organ damage.","Symptoms of hypertensive crisis can include severe headache, dyspnoea, and chest pain.","Immediate management of hypertensive crisis involves reducing blood pressure to prevent further organ damage."],"references":["Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Alley WD, Schick MA. Hypertensive Emergency. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470371/","Rodriguez MA, Kumar SK, De Caro M. Hypertensive crisis. Cardiol Rev. 2010 Mar-Apr;18(2):102-7. doi: 10.1097/CRD.0b013e3181c307b7. PMID: 20160537"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T15:56:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T09:46:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9908"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71166"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"